04333nam a22006135i 9780773585942DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112011xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735859427 a10.1515/97807735859422doi  a(DE-B1597)657804  a(OCoLC)808375345  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aH53.F7bS73 2011 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a300.944091 aStaum, Martin S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNature and Nurture in French Social Sciences, 1859–1914 and Beyond /cMartin S. Staum. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b6 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Ideas ;v5300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction to the Nature-Nurture Debate -- tThe Ethnographers -- tThe Anthropologists -- tRibot and Psychological Heredity -- tHeredity and Milieu in the Revue philosophique -- tAlfred Binet: from Measuring Heads to Testing Intelligence -- tThe Non-Durkheimian Sociologists -- tReorientation of Institutions -- tEchoes in the Vichy Era -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe prevailing assumption has been that French ethnographers highlighted the cultural and social environment while anthropologists emphasized the scientific study of head and body shapes. Martin Staum shows that the temptation to gravitate towards one pole of the nature-nurture continuum often resulted in reluctant concessions to the other side. Psychologists Théodule Ribot and Alfred Binet, for example, were forced to recognize the importance of social factors. Non-Durkheimian sociologists were divided on the issue of race and gender as progressive and tolerant attitudes on race did not necessarily correlate with flexible attitudes on gender. Recognizing this allows Staum to raise questions about the theory of the equivalence of all marginalized groups. Anthropological institutions re-organized before the First World War sometimes showed decreasing confidence in racial theory but failed to abandon it completely. Staum's chilling epilogue discusses how the persistent legacy of such theories was used by extremist anthropologists outside the mainstream to deploy racial ideology as a basis of persecution in the Vichy era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNature and nurture -- France -- History -- 19th century. 0aNature and nurture -- France -- History -- 20th century. 0aNature and nurturezFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aNature and nurturezFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial sciences -- France -- History -- 19th century. 0aSocial sciences -- France -- History -- 20th century. 0aSocial scienceszFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial scienceszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358594240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773585942423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773585942/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  aGBV-deGruyter-alles